## 5. Multi-Sensory Instruction

### Meaning

Multi-sensory instruction is teaching that involves more than one sense (sight, hearing, touch, smell, taste) simultaneously.

### The Five Sense Organs

| Sense | Organ | Stimulus |
|-------|-------|----------|
| Sight | Eyes | Light |
| Hearing | Ears | Sound |
| Touch | Skin | Pressure/touch |
| Smell | Nose | Odor |
| Taste | Tongue | Taste |

### VAKT Approach

| Letter | Meaning | Sense |
|--------|---------|-------|
| V | Visual | Sight |
| A | Auditory | Hearing |
| K | Kinesthetic | Movement |
| T | Tactile | Touch |

### Advantages of Multi-Sensory Instruction

| Advantage | Explanation |
|-----------|-------------|
| **Better retention** | Information processed through multiple pathways |
| **Increased engagement** | More interesting than single-sense learning |
| **Accommodates learning styles** | Suits visual, auditory, kinesthetic learners |
| **Stronger neural connections** | Multiple brain areas activated |
| **More permanent learning** | Less likely to forget |
| **Develops all aspects** | Cognitive, affective, psychomotor |
| **Self-confidence** | Success through multiple channels |

### Applications

1. Science experiments (seeing, touching, smelling)
2. Language learning (hearing, speaking, writing)
3. Art education (seeing, doing, touching)
4. Physical education (movement, touch, sight)

